Communicate Data Findings

Ford GoBike Data Investigation Explanatory Analysis

By: Marwan Selim

Project Overview¶

The Analysis is the final project of Udacity Advanced Data Analytics Nanodegree and it focuses on doing a complete analysis of an actual data set by Ford GoBike.

The project demonstrate the different phases of data analysis including:

1- Data Pulling/Gathering.

2- Preliminary Exploration.

3- Cleaning & Wrangling.

4- Exploratory Data Analysis Visualization.

5- Explanatory Data Visualisation.

The Dataset:¶

Ford GoBike is a data set of trips from February 2019 covering 183,412 entries with 16 initial variables.

The variables can be grouped into:¶

  • Trip Duration (seconds)

  • Start Station (ID, Name, Longitude & Latitude)

  • End Station (ID, Name, Longitude & Latitude)

  • Bike ID

  • Start & End Times

  • User Type, Gender, Birthyear & Whether they use bikeshare for all trips

The Variables are then cleaned & wrangleded to cover 174,668 entries with also 16 variables¶

  • Trip Duration (seconds) & Distance (meters)
  • Start Station (ID & Name)
  • End Station (ID & Name)
  • Bike ID
  • Start & End Hours
  • Start Weekdays
  • Start Date
  • User Type, Gender, Age, Age Group & Whether they use bikeshare for all trips

The Majority of the trips are around the 5 minutes duration and then as the duration increase the number of trips decrease in an inverse exponential manner¶

Most trips are round trips which suggest quick errands or recreational use (the mode = 0) while the one way trips are normally ditributed with some skewing to the left peaking at around 800 meters in distance between the starting & ending stations¶

The above plot shows consistency with the hypothesis of the commuting use case given the higher usage on weekdays with the exeption of Feb 13th & Feb 25th which are against the theory¶

Users are within the age group between 18 & 57 years of age having the mean at around 32 years old, with some outliers between the age of 57 & the age of 120 years¶

The maximum trip distance seem to have an exponential increase with the increase of the duration with the exception of the round trips having a total distance of zero. also, the majority of the trips form a cluster between 5 & 30 minutes and around the 1.5 Km¶

Trip Distances seem to peak in the trips starting at 5 & 8 am and then starts increasing again till it shows a smaller peak at 5pm which is somehow consistent with commuting hours while the 5am trips seem a little bit off but it can still be relatable to higher distance as their expected to take more time¶

Midnight to dawn trips seem to have unusually long durations with a wide margin of error which requires some investigation¶

Looks like the weekend trips increase in the age group between 18-26 & from 60-79. for older age groups we need to zoom in more for further investigation¶

The number of weekend trips increase also with the older age groups which aligns with the recreational trips hypothesis¶

During Weekdays rides demand seem to have a bimodal normal distribution with peaks during commuting times (8am & 5 pm) while it plateaus to be unimodal during weekends which agrees with the dual use hypthesis commuting & recreational¶

Also, During weekdays it seems tht Subscribers have a smaller standard deviation meaning a more solid routine than that of Customers but this consistency flips during weekends¶

There is consistency across genders & age groups regarding more demand on weekdays than weekends & also the age group split with some exceptions regarding the age group distribution in non-binary users as the age groups vary significantly between one day & another & also vary vs. the typical age group split¶

It looks like that females & other genders have more subscribers than customers specially in the older age groups, also the average distance between genders doesn't seem to vary significantly but their error margin seem to increase with the decrease of the number of samples which is logical.¶

weirdly, looks like females & non-binary users above the age of 100 seem to have a very small error margin and they both seem to be solley subscribers.¶

The most obvious error margins are in the age group between 60-79 & highest amongst females & nonbinary users¶

Hours peak during weekdays at 8 am & 17 pm as suggested before in all genders with the exception of Non-Binary as they peak at 5 & 6 pm¶

Thursday seems to have the highest demand in these hours regardless of the gender¶

Finally looks like the percentage of non-binary users on weekend is higher than that of the other genders¶

Key Findings & Insights¶

  • The Analysis showed that the majority of users are subscribers & they mostly use the service for commuting to & from work at peak hours of 8-9 am & 5-6 pm on weekdays.
  • It also shows a unimodal more normally distributed timings on the weekends around the after noon
  • The majority of the users are males with a significant amount of females & around 2% non-binary users
  • Users Age vary significantly between 18 & 140 years old with the majority of the users between 18 & 44 years of age
  • February 13th (a weekday) showed a significant drop in demand & Feb 25th (a weekend) showed an unexplained rise in demand

Key Findings & Insights cont.¶

  • A lot of the trips were noticed to have a zero distance meaning that it's a round trip which suggest their use for running quick errands or recreational use specially that there duration are typically around the 10 minutes mark
  • The Average distance seem to decrease on weekends vs. weekdays while the average duration acts in an opposite manner which could be explained by the fact that people are usually more rushed during commuting times
  • There's an increase in the demand on weekends amongst the youngest & oldest age groups
  • Customers have longer distances & durations vs. the average subscriber
  • The main cluster of data lies below 8 Kms & between the 10 & 60 minutes mark
